Displayed by the CEHTP Science Team</origin> <pubdate>20140624</pubdate> <title>Childhood lead poisoning data for California by county, age, and blood lead level, 2007-2011; and age of housing data and children living in poverty, 2000</title> <onlink>http://www.ehib.org/page.jsp?page_key=457</onlink> </citeinfo> </citation> <descript> <abstract>This dataset contains counts and percentages of blood lead levels among children tested for lead poisoning during 2007-2011 within California .  The data are stratified by county, age, and blood lead level.  The dataset also includes counts and percentages of age of housing and children living in poverty from the 2000 Census.  </abstract> <purpose>To provide data that is consistent with the National Environmental Public Health Tracking Network guidance for creating Nationally Consistent Data and Measures (NCDMs) for lead poisoning.</purpose> <supplinf>These data were provided by the California Childhood Lead Poisoning Prevention Branch (CLPPB) within the California Department of Public Health. Percentage of blood lead levels for counties where fewer than 500 tests were received by CLPPB in a given year are based on small numbers and may fluctuate dramatically from year to year. </complete> <lineage> <procstep> <procdesc>Since 1986, the Childhood Lead Poisoning Prevention Program within the California Department of Public Health, has been legislatively mandated to collect information on childhood blood lead levels (BLL), identify lead burdened children and see that they receive appropriate services, and prevent environmental exposures to lead. This includes maintaining a statewide database, the Response and Surveillance System for Childhood Lead Exposures (RASSCLE II) with blood lead levels and other demographic information about children who have been screened (blood lead tested).    In instances where laboratory results had a detection threshold of 5.0 micrograms per deciliter (\ufffd\ufffdg/dL) and blood measurements were reported at below this level, the result was counted as <4.5 \ufffd\ufffdg/dL. Duplicate children, duplicate blood tests, identified false positive tests, and tests known to be clerical errors have been excluded.  CEHTP obtained blood lead level data from CLPPB and created this dataset to be used for public health surveillance.  The dataset on the CEHTP portal includes counts and percentages of blood lead levels of children tested by county and age (0-<6, 6-<21, and 0-<21). Children are unique per year, only their highest blood lead level is reported. Percentages were calculated by CLPPB by using the total number of children tested in the denominator.   </procdesc> <procdate>20100403</procdate> </procstep> <procstep> <procdesc>Housing information and poverty status about the U.S. population are collected by the U.S. government via the U.S. census every 10 years.  CEHTP downloaded the 2000 age of housing and poverty status data from the Census.gov website and aggregated the data into categories: housing built before 1950, housing built between 1950 and 1979, and housing built before 1979.</procdesc> <procdate>20100901</procdate> </procstep> </lineage> </dataqual> <eainfo> <overview> <eaover>This data contains the following fields: Cnty_FIPS Start_Date End_Date Measure_ID Measure_VA  </eaover> <eadetcit>Age categories are: 0-<6, 6-<21, and 0-<21  Blood lead level categories are: 0 to <4.5 micrograms per deciliter (\ufffd\ufffdg/dL), 4.5 to <9.5 \ufffd\ufffdg/dL, >=9.5 \ufffd\ufffdg/dL</eadetcit> </overview> </eainfo> <distinfo> <distrib> <cntinfo> <cntperp> <cntper>CEHTP Science Team</cntper> <cntorg>CA Department of Public Health, CA Environmental Health Tracking Program</cntorg> </cntperp> <cntpos/> <cntaddr> <addrtype>Mailing</addrtype> <address>850 Marina Bay Parkway, Bldg P, 3rd Floor</address> <city>Richmond</city> <state>CA</state> <postal>94804</postal> <country>United States Of America</country> </cntaddr> <cntvoice>5106203620</cntvoice> <cnttdd/> <cntfax>5106203720</cntfax> <cntemail>data@cehtp.org</cntemail> <hours/> <cntinst/> </cntinfo> </distrib> <resdesc>NA</resdesc> <distliab>Persons or entities given access to restricted data are liable for compliance with conditions set forth in the data use agreement.
